  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Here's a breakdown of some of the most important:\n\n**Key International Instruments:**\n\n*   **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988 Vienna Convention):** This is the first major international treaty to explicitly address money laundering. It requires countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds derived from drug trafficking.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** While not a treaty or law itself, the FATF Recommendations are the global standard for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and proliferation financing. These recommendations provide a comprehensive framework of measures that countries should implement. They are widely adopted and serve as the basis for many national anti-money laundering (AML) laws.\n    *   **The 40 Recommendations (later revised to the 40+9 Recommendations, now just the FATF Recommendations):** These cover a wide range of areas, including:\n        *   Criminalizing money laundering and terrorist financing.\n        *   Establishing customer due diligence (CDD) and record-keeping requirements for financial institutions.\n        *   Reporting suspicious transactions.\n        *   International cooperation, including mutual legal assistance.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000 Palermo Convention):** This convention expands the scope of money laundering offences beyond drug-related crimes to include proceeds from all serious crimes as defined by the convention.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990 Strasbourg Convention):** This convention focuses on enhancing international cooperation in tracing, seizing, and confiscating the proceeds of crime.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime and on the Financing of Terrorism (2005 Warsaw Convention):** This is an update to the Strasbourg Convention that also includes provisions on combating terrorist financing.\n\n**Key Aspects and Principles:**\n\n*   **Criminalization of Money Laundering:** These international instruments require signatory countries to criminalize money laundering, defining it as the process of concealing or disguising the origins of illegally obtained money so that it appears to come from legitimate sources.\n*   **Customer Due Diligence (CDD):** Financial institutions are required to identify and verify the identity of their customers, understand the nature of their business, and monitor their transactions for suspicious activity.\n*   **Suspicious Transaction Reporting (STR):** Financial institutions are obligated to report any transactions that appear suspicious or unusual to the relevant authorities (often a Financial Intelligence Unit - FIU).\n*   **International Cooperation:** International conventions facilitate cooperation between countries in investigating and prosecuting money laundering offences, including the exchange of information, mutual legal assistance, and extradition.\n*   **Confiscation of Assets:** These instruments promote the confiscation of assets derived from criminal activity, including money laundering.\n*   **Extending criminalization beyond drug trafficking:** A key evolution was the move to make money laundering a crime regardless of the predicate offence.\n\n**Impact and Enforcement:**\n\n*   These international laws and standards have prompted countries around the world to enact their own national anti-money laundering (AML) legislation.\n*   The FATF plays a crucial role in monitoring compliance with its recommendations and identifying countries with weak AML regimes.  Countries deemed non-compliant can face sanctions.\n*   International cooperation is essential for effectively combating money laundering, as criminals often move funds across borders to avoid detection.\n\n**In summary, while there's no single \"international law against money laundering,\" there's a robust framework of international conventions, treaties, and standards (primarily the FATF Recommendations) that require countries to criminalize money laundering, implement preventative measures, and cooperate internationally to combat this crime.**  The effectiveness of these measures depends on their implementation and enforcement at the national level.\n",
